04073nam a2200505Ia 9780774818308DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20112010xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748183087 a10.59962/97807748183082doi  a(DE-B1597)671717  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRA450.A4bB87 2010eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a362.1082/0971231 aBurnett, Kristin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTaking Medicine :bWomen's Healing Work and Colonial Contact in Southern Alberta, 1880-1930 /cKristin Burnett. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2011] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b15 b&w photos, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWomen and Indigenous Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Niitsitapi: The Northwestern Plains -- t2 Setting the Stage: Engendering the Therapeutic Culture of the Siksika, Kainai, Piikani, Tsuu T’ina, and Nakoda -- t3 Giving Birth: Women’s Health Work and Western Settlement, 1850-1900 -- t4 Converging Therapeutic Systems: Encounters between Aboriginal and Non-Aboriginal Women, 1870s-90s -- t5 Laying the Foundation: The Work of Nurses, Nursing Sisters, and Female Attendants on Reserves, 1890-1915 -- t6 Taking over the System: Graduate Nurses, Nursing Sisters, Female Attendants, and Indian Health Services, 1915-30 -- t7 The Snake and the Butterfly: Midwifery and Birth Control, 1900s-30s -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe buffalo hunter, the medicine man, and the missionary continue to dominate the history of the North American west, even though historians have recognized women's role as both colonizer and colonized since the 1980s. Kristin Burnett helps to correct this imbalance by investigating the convergence of Aboriginal and settler therapeutic regimes in the Treaty 7 region from the perspective of women. Although the imperial eye focused on medicine men, Aboriginal women played important roles as healers and caregivers, and the knowledge and healing work of both Aboriginal and settler women brought them into contact. But as settlement increased and the colonial regime hardened, informal encounters in domestic spaces gave way to more formal, one-sided interactions in settler-run hospitals and nursing stations. By revealing Aboriginal and settler women's contributions to the development of health care in southern Alberta, Taking Medicine challenges traditional understandings of colonial medicine and nursing in the contact zone.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481830840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774818308423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774818308/original  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles